content: Yes, there have been recent success stories in conservation efforts for endangered species in the Aleutian Islands. One notable example is the recovery of the Aleutian Canada goose, which was once critically endangered with a population of fewer than 800 individuals in the 1970s. Conservation efforts, including habitat restoration and predator control, have helped increase their population to over 70,000 individuals today. Another success story is the removal of non-native foxes from some islands, which has helped protect native bird populations from predation. Additionally, there are ongoing efforts to protect and conserve Steller sea lions, a threatened species found in the Aleutian Islands.
